Lab:SQL injection attack, querying the database type and version on MySQL and Microsoft

This was a UNION attack where the goal was to identify the specific version of the database running on the server. I used simple queries first to determine the number of columns and which ones could hold string data.

I found out the table has two columns. The first column was able to display the output I needed. By using a database-specific global variable, I was able to pull the version information directly into the web page.

As you can see in the image, the injection was a success and it returned the Ubuntu/MySQL version details in the table.

Payload used:
'+UNION+SELECT+@@version,+NULL#

Steps to reproduce:

1.Navigate to a category filter and capture the request in Burp Suite, then send it to Repeater.

2.Use a series of ' ORDER BY X-- or ' UNION SELECT NULL, NULL-- payloads to confirm the table has 2 columns.

3.Test each column to see which one can display string data by replacing NULL with a string like 'a'.

4.Once the display column is found, replace NULL with the MySQL-specific command @@version.

5.Add a comment character (# or -- ) at the end to nullify the rest of the original SQL query.

6.Send the request and locate the database version string (e.g., 8.0.42...) in the rendered HTML response.